    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Thelypteris levyi improperly include inducing nausea, experiencing allergic reactions, causing dizziness, causing diarrhea, and triggering headaches. These side effects can occur due to the presence of toxic compounds such as thelypterine and flavonoids, which can be released when the plant is mishandled or ingested in large quantities. Ingestion of Thelypteris levyi has been reported to cause gastrointestinal symptoms such as diarrhea and nausea due to the plant's high fiber content. Allergic reactions can occur due to the plant's sap, which contains allergenic compounds. Furthermore, the plant's volatile compounds can cause dizziness and headaches when inhaled or ingested in large amounts.",
    "uses": "Thelypteris levyi is a plant species with various traditional uses, including its application in folk medicine for treating various health conditions. It is traditionally used to treat fever, inflammation, and respiratory issues. The plant is also believed to have antimicrobial properties, which can help combat infections. In some regions, Thelypteris levyi is used to treat skin conditions and wounds due to its potential antiseptic properties. However, its efficacy and safety for human consumption and application require further scientific research and validation.",
    "taxonomy": "Thelypteris levyi is classified as a species of fern in the family Thelypteridaceae. It belongs to the genus Thelypteris, which is a group of ferns commonly found in tropical and subtropical regions. The species is further categorized as a member of the Thelypteris genus within the order Polypodiales. This classification is based on its leaf morphology, reproductive structures, and other botanical characteristics. Thelypteris levyi's classification is subject to ongoing research and potential revisions.",
    "benefits": "Thelypteris levyi, also known as the Levy's fern, has been studied for its potential health benefits. Research suggests that the plant may contain antioxidants and anti-inflammatory compounds, which could help protect against cell damage and reduce inflammation. The antioxidants in Levy's fern may also have neuroprotective effects, potentially aiding in the prevention of neurodegenerative diseases. Additionally, the plant has been traditionally used to treat various health conditions, including fever, rheumatism, and skin irritations. Further studies are needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of Thelypteris levyi's health benefits.",
    "parts": "Thelypteris levyi is a species of fern native to the tropical regions of Central and South America. However, there is limited information available on the medicinal properties and uses of this specific plant species. Thelypteris levyi is not widely documented as a medicinal plant, and its uses, if any, are not well-documented or verified by scientific studies. Further research is needed to determine its potential medicinal properties and benefits. Its leaves may possess some medicinal properties, similar to other species of the Thelypteris genus, but this is speculative and requires further investigation.",
    "intro": "Thelypteris levyi, also known as Levy's maiden fern or Maidenhair fern, is a species of fern belonging to the family Thelypteridaceae. This plant is valued for its potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may help to reduce inflammation and protect against oxidative stress. The bioactive constituents of Thelypteris levyi include flavonoids, terpenoids, and phenolic acids, which contribute to its medicinal properties. In traditional herbal medicine, Thelypteris levyi is often used to prepare teas, infusions, and decoctions, as well as being incorporated into salves and creams for topical application."
